Here's the proper approach using MAUI's app lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Restore draft on page load
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated += OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Resumed += OnAppResumed;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();

        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated -= OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Resumed -= OnAppResumed;
    }

    private void OnAppBackgrounded(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Save draft when app loses focus
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnAppResumed(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Restore draft when app returns (handles OS-killed scenarios)
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Call this when the user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Deactivated`** fires when the app goes to background — save here since the OS may kill your app at any time after this.
- **`Resumed`** fires when the app returns to foreground.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text. For larger drafts, use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with file I/O instead.
- Always **unsubscribe** in `OnDisappearing` to avoid leaks.
- Call `ClearDraft()` when the user taps "Save" or "Discard" so stale drafts don't reappear.
